Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Strategic network mapping and gap analysis
Cold outreach message crafting (email, LinkedIn, DM)
"Give before you ask" relationship philosophy
Follow-up cadence and persistence without pestering
Event networking strategies (online and in-person)
Building genuine professional relationships (not transactional)
Mentor-finding and mentor-approaching strategies
Building in public (content as networking magnet)
Warm introduction request scripting
Network maintenance and dormant connection reactivation

Methodologies & Frameworks
Philosophy: Adam Grant's Give and Take (Be a giver), Keith Ferrazzi's Never Eat Alone, Weak ties theory (Granovetter)
Outreach: The 5-sentence cold email, LinkedIn connection + personalized note, Warm intro request template
Network Model: 5-5-5 Rule (5 strong connections + 5 aspirational + 5 you can help), Dunbar's number awareness
Follow-Up: 48-hour follow-up rule, Value-add follow-ups (share article, intro, resource), CRM tracking
Events: Pre-event research, 3-deep-conversation goal (not 30 business cards), Post-event follow-up batch
Content: Build in public, Share learnings, Comment thoughtfully, Create visibility

Reference Documentation
1. Cold Outreach Templates
Comprehensive guide covering:
- The 5-line cold email: Hook (personalized), Context (why you), Ask (specific and small), Value (what's in it for them), Close (easy response)
- LinkedIn connection note: 300 chars max, reference something specific about them
- Warm intro request: "Would you be comfortable introducing me to [name]? I'd love to discuss [specific topic]. Happy if you'd like to check with them first."
- Follow-up after no response: Add value, don't just bump — share something useful

2. Event Networking Playbook
Complete strategy library:
- Pre-event: Research speakers and attendees, set 3 conversation goals
- At event: Ask questions, listen deeply, be genuinely curious
- Don't pitch — express interest in THEIR work
- Exchange contact info organically (don't force business cards)
- Post-event: Send personalized follow-up within 48 hours referencing specific conversation

3. Network Maintenance
Technical reference with:
- Monthly: Reach out to 5 dormant connections with no agenda (share article, congratulate, check in)
- Quarterly: Review network map, identify gaps, set outreach goals
- Annually: "Gift" audit — who helped you this year? Thank them properly
- CRM or spreadsheet: Track last contacted, relationship strength, mutual value
- The "invisible" network: People watching your content who haven't reached out yet

Networking Patterns
Pattern 1: The Value-First Outreach
Building relationships before needing them:
- Research the person: Recent work, posts, achievements
- Lead with genuine value: Share a relevant article, introduce them to someone, or acknowledge their work
- Small ask: "Would you have 15 minutes for a coffee chat about [specific topic]?"
- No pitch: The first interaction should be about THEM, not your needs
- Follow up with a thank you + something useful from the conversation

Pattern 2: The Dormant Connection Reactivation
Rebuilding relationships that went cold:
- Context: "Hey [Name], it's been a while! I was thinking about you when I saw [relevant connection]..."
- No guilt: Don't apologize for not being in touch (everyone's busy)
- Offer value: Share something relevant to their current work
- Light ask: "Would love to catch up sometime — no agenda, just curious how things are going"
- If they're receptive: Schedule a 15-20 minute call or coffee

Pattern 3: Building in Public as a Networking Magnet
Attracting connections through visibility:
- Share 2-3 LinkedIn/Twitter posts per week: Learnings, experiences, hot takes
- Comment thoughtfully on posts by people you want to connect with
- Teach what you know — it positions you as a connector and expert
- DMs after engaging: "Loved your post about X, it reminded me of Y in my work"
- This is long-game networking — compounds over months, not days

Best Practices
Philosophy
- Give before you ask — always lead with value, not requests
- Networking is about PEOPLE, not transactions — genuine curiosity > agenda
- The best networkers are the best listeners and question-askers
- Quality over quantity: 10 genuine relationships > 500 LinkedIn connections
- Your reputation is your network — never burn bridges for short-term gain

Execution
- Follow up within 48 hours — after that, you're forgotten
- Specificity wins: "I enjoyed your talk about XYZ" > "Great to meet you"
- Don't ask for a job in the first interaction — ask for knowledge and insights
- Introduce people who should know each other — becoming a connector is high-status
- Track your network in a simple spreadsheet or CRM — memory fails, systems don't

Mistakes
- Connecting with everyone on LinkedIn without a personalized note — low-value signal
- Only networking when you need something — people can smell desperation
- All take, no give — the transactional networker gets a reputation fast
- Long, rambling outreach messages — keep it to 5 sentences maximum
- Not following up — the meeting is just the beginning, not the end

